DONE: 3 reqs in 0.907s, mean 302.4ms/req

----------------------------------------------------------------------------

Findings
--------

1. Five identical p=512 prefill requests in sequence. Each call hits the
   probe site with cache.entries.len() == 0, and each call enters the
   store site with entries_before == 0. The cache is empty every time
   even though a snapshot was just stored on the previous request.

2. Per-request prefill latency is flat at ~300ms — there is zero TTFT
   gain from repeating the same prompt. If the L1 cache were shared,
   request 2 onward should restore the snapshot and skip prefill
   entirely (~5ms restore vs ~300ms cold prefill, a ~60x gain).

3. The token hash field (5045551469299914854) is identical across all
   five probes and stores, confirming the key matches what was stored.
   The cache instance itself is different — there is no entry to find.

Root cause
----------

crates/ax-engine-server/src/generation/streaming.rs:87 constructs a
fresh `EngineSession` for every /v1/generate/stream request:

    let mut session = EngineSession::new(session_config)?;

`EngineSession::new` builds a fresh `MlxRunner` (via
`crates/ax-engine-sdk/src/session/native.rs:38`), and the runner owns
the prefix cache as a private field:

    crates/ax-engine-mlx/src/runner.rs:2330
        prefix_cache: Mutex<MlxPrefixCache>,

The runner is dropped together with the session at end-of-stream, so
the L1 cache and all its snapshots evaporate. Disk L2 (F3 M2) would
survive but is opt-in via `AX_MLX_PREFIX_CACHE_DIR` and not engaged
in this run.

This is explicitly acknowledged at
`crates/ax-engine-sdk/src/session/mod.rs:58-60`:

  /// For native MLX, blocking generation still constructs a full
  /// `EngineSession` per call so the model and KV state are not
  /// reused. Use `EngineSession` directly for repeated MLX requests.

The acknowledgement was written for the blocking-generate path
(StatelessGenerateContext) but applies equally to streaming/MLX. The
shared `app_state.request_session: Arc<Mutex<EngineSession>>` IS used
by embeddings, metadata, and lifecycle endpoints, but explicitly NOT
by the streaming generate path — presumably to allow concurrent
streams without serializing on a single mutex.

Fix direction (NOT applied here)
--------------------------------

Hoist the `prefix_cache` field (and the disk_prefix_cache pointer)
out of `MlxRunner` into an `Arc<Mutex<MlxPrefixCache>>` carried by
`AppState`, then pass it into each per-request `MlxRunner` via a new
constructor parameter. Concurrent streams keep their own KV state and
runner-local mutables; only the snapshot store/probe path shares the
underlying cache.

This is the highest-impact prefill-side change available given the
diagnostic findings in 1cefd44 / 3f82c20 / f13e691: the existing
TurboQuant / W6 / geglu work is all moot for repeat-prompt traffic
because nothing persists across requests in the first place.
